\af0\afs22\alang1025 \ltrch\fcs0 \f38\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\cgrid\langnp2057\langfenp2057 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12086910 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12086910 
\par COMPLILATION OF MORALE INDICATIONS
\par AS MENTIONED IN PERSONAL CORRESPONDENCE
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6436052 2. RED CROSS PERSONNEL}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12086910 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12086910 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-11\li0\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid11616502 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12086910 
A special morale and security check was made this week on personal letters written by American Red Cross personnel throughout their operations in the region served by this office. The morale check is given in the preceding table. This is much the wors
t morale record of any unit so far checked. In almost every case the percentage of "Bad" comments is very much higher than for any strictly military personnel. Although general morale is bad only in a minority of Red Cross letters, 35%, this is incomparab
l
y higher than the percentage for members of the armed forces, average 2% Complaints of bad health, 77% of references to health, are remarkably numerous. Complaints about rations, 30%, quarters, 46%, and superiors- (tabulated as "officers"), 75% also indic
ate unusually bad morale conditions. Red Cross workers are the only group so far examined in which unfavorable references to the local French, 57% outnumber favorable. Even their reaction to news from home is usually unfavorable.
\par 
\par Only as regards condemnation of mail service, 83% unfavorable, and approval of the British, 100%, do they agree with the reactions of military personnel.
\par 
\par The security record of Red Cross personnel is also outstandingly bad. They show definite improvement (especially in th
e personnel that has been in Algiers for some time) as a result of returns and instructions from this office, but this week 29% of their letters still required some censorship action, mostly excision to prevent revealing localities of A.P.O.'s. This perce
ntage is extraordinarily high and indicates a serious security problem. Although Red Cross personnel is small relative to the military, they write very frequent and often voluminous letters.
\par 
\par On the other hand, references by military personnel to the work done for them by the Red Cross are favorable with few exceptions.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6436052 3. CIVILIAN PERSONNEL}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12086910 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6436052 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12086910 A special check was also made on personal letters of American civilians, other than Red Cross employees, working for the Army or otherwise accredited at th
is headquarters. Some of the data are presented in the preceding table. Although general morale within this group is somewhat lower than for military personnel, it is satisfactory, 91% good in comments in letters. More specific morale reactions resemble t
hose of army officers in most respects. The principal exceptions are that the civilians complain much more about food, 62% of comments bad against an average of only 6 for officers, and about their quarters, 33% bad against average of 8% for officers. The
 morale record of other civilians is uniformly better than for Red Cross employees except as regards complaints about food. This exception doubtless reflects the known excellence of the Red Cross mess in Algiers. It is noteworthy that officers, who certai
nly are fed no better than civilians to whom the army messes are open and who perhaps are not fed as well as Red Cross personnel, complain much less about food than do either of these two civilian groups.
\par 
\par The following comments are believed to be of interest as regards con
ditions among civilians at headquarters and the reaction of some officers working with civilians. (Continents are from letters by civilians unless otherwise noted). Although gathered from the mail of a few days, these are typical of 
remarks common in mail from and about civilians throughout the period of our operation.
\par 
\par "You used the right word when you said you imagined me ensconced in a villa as I am just that. . .}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6436052  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12086910 The Army gave me a guard with the house.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12086910  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12086910 He is very obliging serves me coffee in bed and does all the things for me personally such as clothes pressing shoe shining etc." (N.A.E.B.).}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid12086910 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6436052 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12086910 "The British ration is free, the American costs almost nothing. I don't get enough smokes of the kind I like, but I take everything and I've already got a small hoard locked up in my wardrobe." (AFHQ).}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12086910 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6436052 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12086910 "As I've said before don't let money be a big hurdle. . .The financial situation is bound to improve. . .I go to the 5600 a year bracket without delay. . .Two checks for overtime pay sent to the bank. .}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12086910 
