\par 11. R}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6436052 ELATIONS WITH LOCAL POPULATION}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12086910 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6436052 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12086910 Comments
 on the French are unusually numerous in this week's mail (in 8% of officers' letters) but indicate about the same level of approval (98%). Amorous episodes with local girls seem to be increasing and as the troops move on they give rise to odd attempts to
 write French, G.I. style, such as "Jespere vous alley pardon me," Moi chez est overt a vous," or "J'ai sui bien et jai voulez you etrie bien osee." Evidence of less amorous good relations is also abundant.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15603818 12. RELATIONS WITH BRITISH}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12086910 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15603818 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12086910 References to the British are also unusually numerous, 5% (previous average 2%) and continue at the same high level, 96% favorable.
\par 
